Ritchie traces the contours of the material and social economies of the beach throughout time, covering changes in the social status of beach goers, the technology of transport, and the development of fashion (from nudity to Victorianism and back again), as well as the geographic spread of modern beach-going from England to France, across the Mediterranean, and from nineteenth-century America to the world. And as climate change and rising sea levels erode the familiar faces of our coasts, we are poised for a contemporary reckoning with our relationship—and responsibilities—to our beaches and their ecosystems. The Lure of the Beach demonstrates that whether as a commodified pastoral destination, a site of ecological resplendency, or a flashpoint between private ownership and public access, the history of the beach is a human one that deserves to be told now more than ever before.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aBeachesxSocial aspectsxHistory. 7aHISTORY / World.2bisacsh  a19th century America.  aEngland.  aFrance.  aMediterranean.  aancient Rome.  ababy boomers.  abeach culture.  aclass.  aenvironment.  afashion.  agender.  ageographic spread.  aglobal explosion.  agrowth.  ahistory.  aimpact.  aleisure.  amedieval period.  amodernism.  aocean.  apollution.  apublic health.  areligion.  aresorts.  asalt water therapy.  asea level rise.  asocial status.  atechnology.  atimeshare.  atourist industry.  atravel.  aurban history.  avacation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part 